      Tesla v. JPMorgan
   =20
 =20
In 2014, JPMorgan Chase & Co. bought some warrants from Tesla Inc. JPMorgan=
 paid Tesla something like=C2=A0$130 million for the warrants, give or take=
, and those warrants=C2=A0gave it the option=C2=A0it to buy about 1.9 milli=
on shares of Tesla stock for about $560.64 per share in the summer of 2021.=
[3] Then Tesla=E2=80=99s stock went up a lot, it did a 5-for-1 stock split,=
 and it went up some more. By the summer of 2021, Tesla was trading at arou=
nd $643 per share,[4] and JPMorgan had warrants to buy about 9.5 million sh=
ares at about $112.12 per share.In round numbers, if you can buy 9.5 millio=
n shares for $112.12 each and sell them for $643 each, you will make about =
$5 billion of profit. Subtract the $130 million-ish of premium that JPMorga=
n paid for the warrants in 2014, and you get a trade that made it $4.9 bill=
ion of profit. Last November, JPMorgan sued Tesla demanding an extra $162.2=
 million due to a disagreement about a technical adjustment to the terms of=
 the warrants.=C2=A0This seems very petty!=C2=A0JPMorgan was up $5 billion;=
 let the other $162 million go.Now, to be clear, I am kidding. JPMorgan did=
 not actually make $4.9=C2=A0billion on these warrants. It did not buy the =
warrants as a bet that Tesla=E2=80=99s stock would go way up. That would ha=
ve been a good bet! If it had made that bet, it would be up by $4.9=C2=A0bi=
llion. It did not. It bought those warrants as part of a complex hedging-an=
d-tax-structuring transaction that JPMorgan and three other banks did for T=
esla in connection with a convertible-bond deal. JPMorgan hedged the warran=
ts =E2=80=94=C2=A0with the other parts of the transaction, and/or by=C2=A0s=
horting some Tesla stock[5] =E2=80=94=C2=A0and its hedge went down as the w=
arrant value went up. JPMorgan did not make a bet on Tesla=E2=80=99s stock =
price that paid off to the tune of $4.9 billion. JPMorgan=C2=A0did=C2=A0mak=
e a bet on Tesla=E2=80=99s=C2=A0volatility=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0the more vol=
atile Tesla=E2=80=99s stock was over the last seven years, the more money J=
PMorgan would make on these warrants[6] =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=C2=A0that=C2=A0b=
et also did pretty well, as Tesla has had a crazy last few years.Nonetheles=
s I am telling you this wrong thing because JPMorgan=C2=A0did=C2=A0sue Tesl=
a for that $162.2 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0we  discussed it in November =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and because you=C2=A0do=C2=A0just necessarily look ridiculous c=
oming in to court asking for $162.2 million extra on a trade where you=E2=
=80=99re already up $4.9 billion. =E2=80=9COh no we were hedged,=E2=80=9D y=
ou say, =E2=80=9Cour paper profit on that trade is not what we actually ear=
ned,=E2=80=9D and you are right, but come on man! It=E2=80=99s a bad look. =
After all, Tesla=C2=A0did=C2=A0deliver $5 billion worth of stock to JPMorga=
n, and=C2=A0it=C2=A0wasn=E2=80=99t hedged. That=E2=80=99s just real value i=
t paid out (in stock); asking for more is rough.Yesterday Tesla  filed a co=
unterclaim=C2=A0against JPMorgan and it is pretty compelling. Here is the f=
iling. They do kind of lead with the =E2=80=9Ccome on you already made so m=
uch money=E2=80=9D point:As Tesla=E2=80=99s stock price soared above the St=
rike Price, the Warrants became massively valuable to JPM, enabling the ban=
k to acquire billions of dollars in Tesla shares for a fraction of their cu=
rrent market price.Not satisfied to receive these enormous payouts based on=
 the Strike Price that the parties agreed to, JPM put its thumb on the scal=
e by purporting to unilaterally reduce the Strike Price of the Warrants, fr=
om $560.6388 to just $424.66 per share=E2=80=94and thereby receive a windfa=
ll of an even greater number of Tesla shares when the Warrants expired in 2=
021.=C2=A0The issue, as we discussed last time, is that in August 2018 Elon=
 Musk briefly pretended on Twitter that he was going to take Tesla private =
for $420 per share. If Elon Musk had taken Tesla private, that would have g=
reatly reduced the value of JPMorgan=E2=80=99s warrants, which depends on t=
he volatility of Tesla=E2=80=99s stock; exchanging a volatile stock for $42=
0 in cash would crush that value. After Musk=E2=80=99s tweet, JPMorgan rath=
er hastily adjusted the warrants to reduce the strike price to preserve the=
 value of the warrants; after it became clear that Musk was kidding, JPMorg=
an=C2=A0partially=C2=A0reversed the adjustment, but only partially. The res=
ult is that for roughly a month of uncertainty in 2018 about Musk=E2=80=99s=
 going-private plans, JPMorgan is demanding $162.2 million now. Musk=E2=80=
=99s going-private ideas=C2=A0could have=C2=A0affected the value of JPMorga=
n=E2=80=99s seven-year Tesla warrant trade, and JPMorgan adjusted that trad=
e as though they had, but in fact they didn=E2=80=99t. Tesla volatility pro=
mptly bounced back to where it was before his tweets =E2=80=94=C2=A0higher,=
 actually =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the warrant ended up being even more valuable =
to JPMorgan than it had expected. It makes no real sense for JPMorgan to co=
mplain. From Tesla=E2=80=99s filing:Although JPM purported to assume that t=
he Warrants would exhibit reduced volatility from August 2018 forward, this=
 assertion had no support in contemporaneous market data or common sense. O=
n the contrary, JPM pocketed enormous profits as Tesla=E2=80=99s stock pric=
e, and the Warrants=E2=80=99 implied volatility, soared to unprecedented he=
ights through the Warrants=E2=80=99 expiration dates in 2021. ...Indeed, wh=
en JPM announced its initial adjustment to the Strike Price, the Warrants=
=E2=80=99 long-term implied volatility was far above the levels assumed in =
JPM=E2=80=99s calculation. As a result, JPM=E2=80=99s adjustment to the Str=
ike Price secured a commercially unreasonable profit for itself that was no=
t reasonably related to any alleged effect of the tweet. ...JPM=E2=80=99s c=
ommercially unreasonable failure to fully reverse the purported First Adjus=
tment became even more indefensible with time, as volatility rose to levels=
 not seen during or prior to August 2018. ... Tesla=E2=80=99s option-implie=
d volatilities traded at elevated levels for months after August 2018 and e=
xploded to unprecedented levels in 2020 and 2021. Tesla=E2=80=99s soaring i=
mplied volatility gave the lie to JPM=E2=80=99s bad-faith contention that i=
t was entitled to a lower Strike Price due to the Warrants=E2=80=99 suppose=
dly muted implied volatility.It is worth mentioning =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Tesl=
a does mention =E2=80=94=C2=A0that three=C2=A0other=C2=A0banks had bought s=
imilar warrants from Tesla in the same transaction as JPMorgan, and none of=
 them thought to adjust their warrants for Musk=E2=80=99s tweeting.=C2=A0I =
am actually a bit at a loss about what is going on here? One possibility is=
 that JPMorgan=E2=80=99s derivatives trading desk really did think that the=
 right thing to do in 2018 was to adjust the warrants, they then hedged the=
 trade based on a lower strike price for three years, and reversing the adj=
ustment now would cause them to=C2=A0lose=C2=A0money. That seems weird but =
not impossible.Tesla=E2=80=99s explanation is simpler:The windfall JPM dema=
nded bore no relationship to any purported economic effect on the Warrants.=
 On information and belief, JPM pressed its exorbitant demand as an act of =
retaliation against Tesla both for it having passed over JPM in major busin=
ess deals and out of senior JPM executives=E2=80=99 animus toward Mr. Musk.=
=C2=A0That seems to tie to this Wall Street Journal article about how =E2=
=80=9CElon Musk and Jamie Dimon don=E2=80=99t get along,=E2=80=9D which not=
es that=C2=A0JPMorgan hasn=E2=80=99t done any Tesla investment banking work=
 since 2016=C2=A0and has missed out on some opportunities to finance Tesla=
=E2=80=99s cars. I guess? It seems odd to file a nine-digit lawsuit about c=
orporate events adjustments in equity derivatives trades out of personal pi=
que, but odd things do happen a lot to Tesla.
