      Non-deal roadshows
   =20
 =20
Here is a basic model of investment bank research:=09Big institutional inve=
stors like to meet with the managers of the companies whose stocks they tra=
de, so that they can find out useful information about those companies and =
use it to make informed investing decisions.=09These investors are correct =
that these meetings are useful: Investors who meet with managers are more l=
ikely to trade and their trades are likely to be better.=09Wall Street rese=
arch analysts are largely in the business of arranging those meetings: They=
 are intermediaries between corporate managers and big institutional invest=
ors, and so they set up meetings between them at investor conferences,=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cnon-deal roadshows=E2=80=9D (where a company=E2=80=99s executiv=
es fly around to meet with investors), etc.=09Wall Street research analysts=
 are evaluated by their investor customers, and thus ultimately paid, based=
 in large part on how good they are at setting up these meetings, because t=
hese meetings are very useful to the investors.=09Wall Street research anal=
ysts also write research reports with =E2=80=9CBuy=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CHol=
d=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CSell=E2=80=9D recommendations on them, which the inv=
estors also read I guess. The corporate managers can also read them.=09The =
institutional investors may find the research reports useful but they do no=
t care very much about the recommendations at the=C2=A0top; they employ the=
ir own analysts and make their own buy/sell/hold decisions.=09The corporate=
 managers do not find the reports all that useful but they care very much a=
bout the recommendations, and get very mad at analysts who tell their clien=
ts to sell their company=E2=80=99s stock.=09Therefore an analyst who is luk=
ewarm on a company can do a better job=C2=A0for her investor customers=C2=
=A0by writing thoughtful research reports full of interesting facts, slappi=
ng a =E2=80=9CBuy=E2=80=9D recommendation on top, and developing a good rel=
ationship with the company=E2=80=99s managers so she can set up lots of mee=
tings between the managers and the investors.I have written about this mode=
l a lot. It seems fairly straightforward, but there are some non-obvious el=
ements. For instance, Points 1 and 2 are weird insofar as, in the U.S., Reg=
ulation FD prohibits companies from giving =E2=80=9Cmaterial nonpublic info=
rmation" to investors (or analysts) in private meetings without simultaneou=
sly disclosing it to all shareholders. If investors think that these meetin=
gs are useful, and if the meetings are in fact useful, then isn=E2=80=99t t=
hat a Reg FD violation?Also, Point 8 is weird insofar as the most=C2=A0obvi=
ous=C2=A0work product of a research analyst =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the one that=
 regulators seem to care most about =E2=80=94=C2=A0is the buy/sell/hold rec=
ommendation. =E2=80=9CBank X Analyst Upgrades Company Y to Buy=E2=80=9D is =
a headline, =E2=80=9CBank X Analyst Sets Up Productive Meeting Between Comp=
any Y Executives and Hedge Fund Z Portfolio Manager=E2=80=9D is not. Intuit=
ively, Hedge Fund Z would=C2=A0much=C2=A0rather have a good meeting with th=
e executives =E2=80=94=C2=A0where it can ask its own questions about what i=
t wants to know =E2=80=94=C2=A0than have the analyst=E2=80=99s buy/sell/hol=
d recommendation reflect her true feelings about Company Y; Hedge Fund Z si=
mply doesn=E2=80=99t care about the analyst=E2=80=99s true feelings. But Ba=
nk X=E2=80=99s retail clients=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t get to meet with corporate=
 executives, and do get to read the bank=E2=80=99s research reports, and th=
ey may not read much past the buy/sell/hold recommendation. If those recomm=
endations are biased by the need to maintain relationships for the analyst=
=E2=80=99s most important job of=C2=A0setting up meetings, then those retai=
l investors might feel deceived.=C2=A0Here=E2=80=99s a paper by Daniel Brad=
ley, Russell Jame and Jared Williams on =E2=80=9CNon-Deal Roadshows, Inform=
ed Trading, and Analyst Conflicts of Interest=E2=80=9D (in the Journal of F=
inance in November, SSRN version here). Here is the abstract:Non-deal roads=
hows (NDRs) are private meetings between management and institutional inves=
tors, typically organized by sell-side analysts. We find that around NDRs, =
local institutional investors trade heavily and profitably, while retail tr=
ading is significantly less informed. Analysts who sponsor NDRs issue signi=
ficantly more optimistic recommendations and target prices, together with m=
ore =E2=80=9Cbeatable=E2=80=9D earnings forecasts, consistent with analysts=
 issuing strategically biased forecasts to win NDR business. Our results su=
ggest that NDRs result in a substantial information advantage for instituti=
onal investors and create significant conflicts of interests for the analys=
ts who organize them.If a bank brings a company=E2=80=99s managers to town,=
 then (1) institutional investors in that town trade more, (2) their tradin=
g is better informed, (3) they will pay the bank more in commissions to rew=
ard it for setting up the meetings,=C2=A0(4) the bank=E2=80=99s analyst is =
more likely to be bullish on the company=E2=80=99s stock and (5) the bank=
=E2=80=99s analyst is more likely to be=C2=A0bearish on its near-term earni=
ngs, making her earnings target easier to beat.=C2=A0This is all very intui=
tive! And also apparently true.
