 Here is where you email me to say =E2=80=9Cactually with payment for order=
 flow every stock trade *does* involve being ripped off by a more sophistic=
ated counterparty,=E2=80=9D but even you don=E2=80=99t really believe that.=
=C2=A0[3] We discussed these transactions previously  here, and the rest of=
 this footnote will make no sense unless you read that discussion (or even =
if you did!). But for my numbers in the text, see, e.g., page 79 here (for =
strike prices and aggregate warrant premium), paragraph 43 here (for expira=
tion) and paragraph 2 here (for the 1.9 million shares). The =E2=80=9C$130 =
million=E2=80=9D is a bit of a guess: Tesla disclosed (pages 78-79 here) th=
at it paid a total of about $603.4 million for bond hedges on two series of=
 notes, and got back about $389.2 million for the warrants; other evidence =
suggests about two-thirds of that value had to do with the 2021 convertible=
 notes/note hedges/warrants at issue here (with warrants on 3.8 million sha=
res), and the other one-third with the 2019 notes. In its counterclaim Tesl=
a says that it paid JPMorgan $199 million for the bond hedge (paragraph 15)=
, and got some money back on the warrants, though it does not say how much.=
 That $199 million ties well to the $603.4 million in the previous sentence=
: JPMorgan had about half (1.9 million out of 3.8 million shares) of the 20=
21 bond hedge (about $400 million), or about one-third of the total bond he=
dges, so it received about $199 million of premium. Applying the same rough=
 math to the warrant and you get JPMorgan paying about $130 million (one-th=
ird of the total warrant premium). But there=E2=80=99s no reason for the wa=
rrant values to be in linear proportion to the bond hedge ones, so JPMorgan=
 could well have paid $110 million or $140 million or whatever for its slic=
e of the warrants and I would not be surprised. One could do a better job w=
ith a Black-Scholes calculator but honestly the difference is not gonna be =
material in the scheme of things.[4] The average of the closing prices betw=
een June 3 and July 29, the averaging period of the warrants (see paragraph=
 43 here), was $642.95. That is not how the warrants actually do the averag=
ing =E2=80=94=C2=A0they=E2=80=99d use an average of daily volume-weighted a=
verage prices =E2=80=94=C2=A0but again we are looking for approximate numbe=
rs.[5] JPMorgan sold Tesla a =E2=80=9Cbond hedge,=E2=80=9D an option to buy=
 the same number of shares of=C2=A0Tesla stock at a lower price than the wa=
rrant strike price. (See, again,  our previous discussion for more on the l=
ogic here.) So initially JPMorgan was net *short* Tesla stock options, and =
hedged by *buying* Tesla stock. Over time, though, as the convertible notes=
 were converted and as the warrant moved in-the-money, this reversed, and s=
urely by like early 2021 JPMorgan=E2=80=99s hedge would have been to be sho=
rt Tesla stock.[6] Again (see previous footnote) this is complicated by the=
 bond hedge, which is a bet the other way. Net JPMorgan was probably=C2=A0s=
hort a bit of volatility at the start of this trade; really this was a bet =
on skew (the difference in volatility between the two options) and not just=
 volatility.=C2=A0
