<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">NFT HFT</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A share of Microsoft Corp. stock trade=
s for about $300. That price goes up and down, but at any given minute duri=
ng regular trading hours if you want to sell a share of Microsoft stock you=
=E2=80=99re going to sell it within a few pennies of the last trading price=
. If you tried to sell a share of Microsoft for $100 you=E2=80=99d have a h=
ard time doing it. If you called your broker, or went into your broker=E2=
=80=99s app, and said =E2=80=9Csell Microsoft for $100,=E2=80=9D you=E2=80=
=99d get back an instant confirmation saying =E2=80=9Ccongratulations you s=
old Microsoft for $300.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ther=
e are many people in the stock market who would describe themselves as bein=
g in the business of buying underpriced stocks, but they don=E2=80=99t mean=
 it <em>literally</em>. They mean that they pay $300 for stocks that trade =
for $300 because they think those stocks will eventually=C2=A0trade for $50=
0. They don=E2=80=99t mean that they pay $100 for stocks that currently tra=
de at $300. That=E2=80=99s not a business.[1] You could write an algorithm =
saying =E2=80=9Cif anyone is selling Microsoft for $100, buy it,=E2=80=9D b=
ut that would not work. In all likelihood you=E2=80=99d never buy a single =
share. And if you did, that would mean that either=C2=A0(1) it was a =E2=80=
=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26482321.283628=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnlzZS5jb20vcHVibGljZG9jcy9ueXNlL21hcmtldHMvbnlzZS9DbGVhcm=
x5X0Vycm9uZW91c19FeGVjdXRpb25fUnVsZV9hbmRfUHJvY2VkdXJlX0NoYW5nZXMucGRm/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4a459fed" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">clearly erroneous</a>=E2=80=9D trade=
 and the stock exchange will=C2=A0reverse it or (2) something horrible has =
happened to Microsoft and you paid $100 for a stock that=E2=80=99s now wort=
h $80.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile in the market for, like, b=
aseball cards, or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
26482321.283628/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmFydG5ldC5jb20vbWFya2V0L2F0dGljLWNhcnZhZ2d=
pby0xNzEtbWlsbGlvbi1hdWN0aW9uLWVzdGltYXRlLTE0NzcxMTE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBf72d8fc8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">Caravaggios</a>, it is entirely possible to wander int=
o a garage sale and buy an object for far less than its market value. The o=
bjects are unique, the markets are not transparent, the sellers might not b=
e sophisticated, and there are plenty of opportunities for a well-informed =
buyer to underpay a poorly informed seller. On the other hand for all of th=
ose reasons it is also very difficult to write an algorithm saying =E2=80=
=9Cif anyone is selling a Caravaggio for $100, buy it.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=
=99s a good algorithm! But hard to implement on a computer.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">The market for non-fungible tokens is fascinating in that =
it takes the transparency, speed, centralized liquidity and electronic algo=
rithmic trading of the modern stock market, and combines them with garage-s=
ale-like <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26482321.=
283628/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMjQv=
aG93LXRyYWRlcnMtYm91Z2h0LTEtbWlsbGlvbi1pbi1uZnRzLWF0LW1hc3NpdmUtZGlzY291bnQ=
tZHVlLXRvLWFuLW9wZW5zZWEtYnVnP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZW=
RpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDEyNSZ1dG1fY2Ftc=
GFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa387aa81" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> opportuni=
ties to rip off naive rubes</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Savvy opportunists managed to buy more than $1 million in non-fungible to=
kens (NFTs) from OpenSea, the largest market for such digital assets, at ol=
der and significantly lower prices by exploiting a bug in how the platform =
managed active listings. Attackers exploited users who had transferred thei=
r previously listed NFTs to other wallets without having canceled the listi=
ngs.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bug gave its exploiters the abilit=
y to buy those NFTs on the cheap, at their earlier listed price, and then s=
ell them at much higher current market rates. And it left the unwitting NFT=
 owners nursing thousands of dollars of losses, according to Elliptic, the =
blockchain analytics company that identified the anomalous transactions.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a bit like being on eBa=
y and listing something for sale,=E2=80=9D said Tom Robinson, chief scienti=
st and founder of Elliptic. =E2=80=9CIf you want to increase the price of t=
his, you wouldn=E2=80=99t create a new listing and leave the old one going.=
 You=E2=80=99d replace that listing. The problem here is that people aren=
=E2=80=99t cancelling the original listing.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Sellers who want to cancel their listings on NFT platforms have t=
o send messages over the blockchain, and that requires them to pay transact=
ion or =E2=80=9Cgas=E2=80=9D fees, Robinson said.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">NFT users tend to have multiple wallets, and so to circumvent =
the fees, Robinson believes some users may have simply been transferring th=
eir NFTs to a different one. But if they transferred those NFTs back into t=
he original wallets, that original listing =E2=80=94 and its old sale price=
 =E2=80=94 becomes viable and can be used by buyers. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The loophole demonstrates the extent to which the user=
 experience decisions made by the biggest platforms in crypto can lead to e=
xpensive mistakes by even their most sophisticated (and wealthy) customers.=
 OpenSea said it was implementing a number of interface changes designed to=
 =E2=80=9Cmake users aware of all their listings=E2=80=9D to reduce the lik=
elihood of these hidden sales, with more changes expected.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">According to OpenSea data analyzed by Bloomberg News, user =
jpegdegenlove made at least 340 ETH (about $800,000 at current prices) in j=
ust a matter of hours by exploiting the OpenSea bug and selling at least fi=
ve NFTs, three of which were from the Bored Ape Yacht Club collection. Asse=
ts in several collections were affected, including Cool Cats, Mutant Ape Ya=
cht Club and CyberKongz.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So yo=
u <em>can=C2=A0</em>write an algorithm to automatically buy Bored Apes belo=
w the market price, and it will buy=C2=A0apes, and you can keep them. And n=
ot even from rubes! =E2=80=9CEven their most sophisticated (and wealthy) cu=
stomers=E2=80=9D! To fall victim to this trade you had to have been moving =
NFTs around between wallets to minimize gas fees. You thought you were bein=
g clever, but there are always people who are cleverer than you are, and cr=
ypto markets are very good at distinguishing the clever people from the cle=
verer ones and letting the cleverer ones take the clever ones=E2=80=99 mone=
y. Or apes.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is worth spending a minute o=
n long-term incentives here. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/26482321.283628/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMTEvd2hvLWNhbi1yZXNpc3QtdGhlLWNyeXB0by1ib29tP2NtcGlk=
PUJCRDAxMjUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV=
0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDEyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBad140a7a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked a couple of weeks ago</a> about tradi=
tional electronic market-making firms who are getting into crypto. I wrote:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Being a stock-trading middlema=
n was a good way to make a fortune, back when stock trading was dominated b=
y big inefficient banks and there was lots of room for new competition. Now=
 it=E2=80=99s, you know, fine, but it=E2=80=99s efficient and grueling and =
you fight for every basis point and also you get to be the subject of congr=
essional hearings and weird conspiracy theories.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Meanwhile in crypto! Meanwhile in crypto people will pay millions of =
dollars for a JPEG of an ape and then hand over the private key to anyone w=
ho asks nicely! Meanwhile in crypto you can make huge profits by being the =
robot counterparty to fat-finger trades, and no exchange will break those t=
rades!</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the long run this se=
ems bad. There=E2=80=99s a reason that the New York Stock Exchange tries to=
 prevent =E2=80=9Cclearly erroneous=E2=80=9D trades, and reverses them if t=
hey accidentally happen, and the reason is not that the NYSE and its major =
stakeholders are gentle altruists. The reason is that people will trade a l=
ot more stock if their trades on the NYSE work more or less the way they=E2=
=80=99re supposed to. If trading stocks meant constantly being ripped off b=
y more sophisticated counterparties, nobody would do it, and the sophistica=
ted counterparties would have nobody to trade with.[2] It is better for the=
 sophisticated counterparties to pass up some opportunities to rip off the =
rubes, to agree to some rules to level the playing field, to forgo some of =
the rewards to sophistication, in order to increase the size of the pie.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, in the early days of a mar=
ket, it is fun to be sophisticated and take advantage of the people who are=
n=E2=80=99t!</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto=
