g/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc153a937" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> filed a counterclaim</a>=C2=
=A0against JPMorgan and it is pretty compelling. Here is <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26482321.283628/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMu=
YndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3J4RGttZkpYTlB0by92MA/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB48e74a8d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the filing</a>. They do kind of lead=
 with the =E2=80=9Ccome on you already made so much money=E2=80=9D point:</=
p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As Tesla=E2=80=99s stock price s=
oared above the Strike Price, the Warrants became massively valuable to JPM=
, enabling the bank to acquire billions of dollars in Tesla shares for a fr=
action of their current market price.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not s=
atisfied to receive these enormous payouts based on the Strike Price that t=
he parties agreed to, JPM put its thumb on the scale by purporting to <em>u=
nilaterally reduce</em> the Strike Price of the Warrants, from $560.6388 to=
 just $424.66 per share=E2=80=94and thereby receive a windfall of an even g=
reater number of Tesla shares when the Warrants expired in 2021.=C2=A0</p><=
/blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The issue, as we discussed last ti=
me, is that in August 2018 Elon Musk briefly pretended on Twitter that he w=
as going to take Tesla private for $420 per share. If Elon Musk had taken T=
esla private, that would have greatly reduced the value of JPMorgan=E2=80=
=99s warrants, which depends on the volatility of Tesla=E2=80=99s stock; ex=
changing a volatile stock for $420 in cash would crush that value. After Mu=
sk=E2=80=99s tweet, JPMorgan rather hastily adjusted the warrants to reduce=
 the strike price to preserve the value of the warrants; after it became cl=
ear that Musk was kidding, JPMorgan=C2=A0<em>partially=C2=A0</em>reversed t=
he adjustment, but only partially. The result is that for roughly a month o=
f uncertainty in 2018 about Musk=E2=80=99s going-private plans, JPMorgan is=
 demanding $162.2 million now. Musk=E2=80=99s going-private ideas=C2=A0<em>=
could have=C2=A0</em>affected the value of JPMorgan=E2=80=99s seven-year Te=
sla warrant trade, and JPMorgan adjusted that trade as though they had, but=
 in fact they didn=E2=80=99t. Tesla volatility promptly bounced back to whe=
re it was before his tweets =E2=80=94=C2=A0higher, actually =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
and the warrant ended up being even more valuable to JPMorgan than it had e=
xpected. It makes no real sense for JPMorgan to complain. From Tesla=E2=80=
=99s filing:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Although JPM purpo=
rted to assume that the Warrants would exhibit reduced volatility from Augu=
st 2018 forward, this assertion had no support in contemporaneous market da=
ta or common sense. On the contrary, JPM pocketed enormous profits as Tesla=
=E2=80=99s stock price, and the Warrants=E2=80=99 implied volatility, soare=
d to unprecedented heights through the Warrants=E2=80=99 expiration dates i=
n 2021. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Indeed, when JPM announced its =
initial adjustment to the Strike Price, the Warrants=E2=80=99 long-term imp=
lied volatility was far above the levels assumed in JPM=E2=80=99s calculati=
on. As a result, JPM=E2=80=99s adjustment to the Strike Price secured a com=
mercially unreasonable profit for itself that was not reasonably related to=
 any alleged effect of the tweet. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPM=
=E2=80=99s commercially unreasonable failure to fully reverse the purported=
 First Adjustment became even more indefensible with time, as volatility ro=
se to levels not seen during or prior to August 2018. ... Tesla=E2=80=99s o=
ption-implied volatilities traded at elevated levels for months after Augus=
t 2018 and exploded to unprecedented levels in 2020 and 2021. Tesla=E2=80=
=99s soaring implied volatility gave the lie to JPM=E2=80=99s bad-faith con=
tention that it was entitled to a lower Strike Price due to the Warrants=E2=
=80=99 supposedly muted implied volatility.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">It is worth mentioning =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Tesla does mention =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0that three=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>banks had bought similar=
 warrants from Tesla in the same transaction as JPMorgan, and none of them =
thought to adjust their warrants for Musk=E2=80=99s tweeting.=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am actually a bit at a loss about what is going =
on here? One possibility is that JPMorgan=E2=80=99s derivatives trading des=
k really did think that the right thing to do in 2018 was to adjust the war=
rants, they then hedged the trade based on a lower strike price for three y=
ears, and reversing the adjustment now would cause them to=C2=A0<em>lose=C2=
=A0</em>money. That seems weird but not impossible.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Tesla=E2=80=99s explanation is simpler:</p><blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">The windfall JPM demanded bore no relationship to any pur=
ported economic effect on the Warrants. On information and belief, JPM pres=
sed its exorbitant demand as an act of retaliation against Tesla both for i=
t having passed over JPM in major business deals and out of senior JPM exec=
utives=E2=80=99 animus toward Mr. Musk.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">That seems to tie to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/26482321.283628/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9q=
cG1vcmdhbnMtamFtaWUtZGltb24tYW5kLXRlc2xhcy1lbG9uLW11c2stZmV1ZC1iZWhpbmQtdGh=
lLXNjZW5lcy0xMTYzNzU4NjAwMQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdb74845b" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">this=
 Wall Street Journal article</a> about how =E2=80=9CElon Musk and Jamie Dim=
on don=E2=80=99t get along,=E2=80=9D which notes that=C2=A0JPMorgan hasn=E2=
=80=99t done any Tesla investment banking work since 2016=C2=A0and has miss=
ed out on some opportunities to finance Tesla=E2=80=99s cars. I guess? It s=
eems odd to file a nine-digit lawsuit about corporate events adjustments in=
 equity derivatives trades out of personal pique, but odd things do happen =
a lot to Tesla.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpad=
