</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a basic model of investment ba=
nk research:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; =
margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Big institutional inv=
estors like to meet with the managers of the companies whose stocks they tr=
ade, so that they can find out useful information about those companies and=
 use it to make informed investing decisions.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">These investors are correct that these meetings are useful: Inv=
estors who meet with managers are more likely to trade and their trades are=
 likely to be better.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Wall Street =
research analysts are largely in the business of arranging those meetings: =
They are intermediaries between corporate managers and big institutional in=
vestors, and so they set up meetings between them at investor conferences,=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cnon-deal roadshows=E2=80=9D (where a company=E2=80=99s execu=
tives fly around to meet with investors), etc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">Wall Street research analysts are evaluated by their investor =
customers, and thus ultimately paid, based in large part on how good they a=
re at setting up these meetings, because these meetings are very useful to =
the investors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Wall Street researc=
h analysts also write research reports with =E2=80=9CBuy=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=
=9CHold=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CSell=E2=80=9D recommendations on them, which t=
he investors also read I guess. The corporate managers can also read them.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The institutional investors may fi=
nd the research reports useful but they do not care very much about the rec=
ommendations at the=C2=A0top; they employ their own analysts and make their=
 own buy/sell/hold decisions.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The =
corporate managers do not find the reports all that useful but they care ve=
ry much about the recommendations, and get very mad at analysts who tell th=
eir clients to sell their company=E2=80=99s stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">Therefore an analyst who is lukewarm on a company can do a=
 better job=C2=A0<em>for her investor customers=C2=A0</em>by writing though=
tful research reports full of interesting facts, slapping a =E2=80=9CBuy=E2=
=80=9D recommendation on top, and developing a good relationship with the c=
ompany=E2=80=99s managers so she can set up lots of meetings between the ma=
nagers and the investors.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26482321.283628/aHR0cH=
