 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">Regulation FD</a> prohibits companies from giving =E2=80=
=9Cmaterial nonpublic information" to investors (or analysts) in private me=
etings without simultaneously disclosing it to all shareholders. If investo=
rs think that these meetings are useful, and if the meetings are in fact us=
eful, then isn=E2=80=99t that a Reg FD violation?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Also, Point 8 is weird insofar as the most=C2=A0<em>obvious=C2=A0</e=
m>work product of a research analyst =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the one that regula=
tors seem to care most about =E2=80=94=C2=A0is the buy/sell/hold recommenda=
tion. =E2=80=9CBank X Analyst Upgrades Company Y to Buy=E2=80=9D is a headl=
ine, =E2=80=9CBank X Analyst Sets Up Productive Meeting Between Company Y E=
xecutives and Hedge Fund Z Portfolio Manager=E2=80=9D is not. Intuitively, =
Hedge Fund Z would=C2=A0<em>much=C2=A0</em>rather have a good meeting with =
the executives =E2=80=94=C2=A0where it can ask its own questions about what=
 it wants to know =E2=80=94=C2=A0than have the analyst=E2=80=99s buy/sell/h=
old recommendation reflect her true feelings about Company Y; Hedge Fund Z =
simply doesn=E2=80=99t care about the analyst=E2=80=99s true feelings. But =
Bank X=E2=80=99s retail clients=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t get to meet with corpora=
te executives, and do get to read the bank=E2=80=99s research reports, and =
they may not read much past the buy/sell/hold recommendation. If those reco=
mmendations are biased by the need to maintain relationships for the analys=
t=E2=80=99s <em>most important job of=C2=A0setting up meetings</em>, then t=
hose retail investors might feel deceived.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a paper by Daniel Bradley, Russell Jame and Jared Will=
iams on =E2=80=9CNon-Deal Roadshows, Informed Trading, and Analyst Conflict=
