-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">here</a>). Here is the abstract:</p><blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Non-deal roadshows (NDRs) are private meetings betwe=
en management and institutional investors, typically organized by sell-side=
 analysts. We find that around NDRs, local institutional investors trade he=
avily and profitably, while retail trading is significantly less informed. =
Analysts who sponsor NDRs issue significantly more optimistic recommendatio=
ns and target prices, together with more =E2=80=9Cbeatable=E2=80=9D earning=
s forecasts, consistent with analysts issuing strategically biased forecast=
s to win NDR business. Our results suggest that NDRs result in a substantia=
l information advantage for institutional investors and create significant =
conflicts of interests for the analysts who organize them.</p></blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If a bank brings a company=E2=80=99s managers =
to town, then (1) institutional investors in that town trade more, (2) thei=
r trading is better informed, (3) they will pay the bank more in commission=
s to reward it for setting up the meetings,=C2=A0(4) the bank=E2=80=99s ana=
lyst is more likely to be bullish on the company=E2=80=99s stock and (5) th=
e bank=E2=80=99s analyst is more likely to be=C2=A0<em>bearish </em>on its =
near-term earnings, making her earnings target easier to beat.=C2=A0This is=
 all very intuitive! And also apparently true.</p><table class=3D"header" w=
idth=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
